# **Patientli “Looks” Platform**

## **Product Requirements Summary (Phase 1 \+ Phase 2\)**

### **Document Purpose**

This document outlines functional and technical requirements for the Patientli “Looks” platform—a modular, token-based website and branding system for healthcare practices. The system supports a **pre-sale interactive demo experience** and a **post-purchase self-serve editing experience**, with AI-assisted updates and optional human support.

---

## **1\. Product Overview**

Patientli “Looks” allows healthcare practices to preview, customize, and purchase high-quality website and brand designs before committing. Users can:

* Browse demo sites

* Modify visual styles in real time (fonts, colors, imagery)

* See industry-specific, personalized content

* Purchase a configured site

* Edit content post-purchase via AI or human support

The system is designed to reduce manual design overhead while increasing conversion and perceived personalization.

---

## **2\. Core Design Principles**

* **Token-based system** (design \+ content)

* **Real-time preview**

* **Low-friction pre-sale experience**

* **Self-serve post-purchase edits**

* **Human support always available**

* **Healthcare-specific content by default**

---

## **3\. Phase One: Pre-Sale Demo & Customization**

### **3.1 Demo Site Gallery**

**Requirements**

* A gallery of demo websites/layouts (“Looks”)

* Each demo represents a baseline configuration

* Demos are publicly accessible (no login required)

**User Actions**

* Browse demo sites

* Select a starting layout/look

### **3.2 Real-Time Style Switching**

**Requirements**

Users can modify the demo site via UI controls:

* **Typography**

  * Switch between approved font sets

* **Color palettes**

  * Swap predefined color schemes

* **Image styles**

  * Choose from image “moods” or packs (e.g., conservative, inclusive, modern)

**Behavior**

* Changes apply instantly

* No page reloads

* Changes are reversible

---

### **3.3 Token System (Design)**

All visual styles must be driven by tokens, including:

* Font families

* Font sizes

* Color variables

* Image references

* UI component styles

Tokens should be:

* Centrally managed

* Easily swappable

* Persistable (saved with configuration)

---

### **3.4 Industry-Specific Content Personalization**

**Requirements**

* Users select an industry/specialty (e.g., dental, optometry)

* Demo site auto-populates with relevant:

  * Page copy

  * Service descriptions

  * Example imagery

**Goal**

Avoid “generic theme” feel—demo should feel pre-built for the user’s practice type by drawing on style tokens which are tagged for use with that practice type.

---

### **3.5 Practice-Level Personalization**

**User Inputs**

For both lead generation and personalization purposes, user should be able to update:

* Practice name

* Address

* Phone number

* Optional logo upload

**Optional**

* Choose from logo style presets if no logo exists  
* Browse brand names and logos that are available for purchase (all names and logos on patient.li/looks

**Behavior**

* Inputs immediately update site preview

* Branding tokens update accordingly

---

### **3.6 Purchase Flow**

**Requirements**

After a user is satisfied with their site, they should be able to sign up for a plan to launch it. 

* Final configuration (tokens \+ content) is saved

* User can:

  * Add configuration to cart

  * Proceed to checkout

* Configuration becomes the baseline for site launch

---

## **4\. Phase Two: Post-Purchase Editing Experience**

### **4.1 Client Dashboard**

**Requirements**

* Secure login for purchased clients

* Dashboard includes:

  * Site preview

  * Editing interface

  * Support access

---

### **4.2 AI-Powered Content Editing**

**Core Concept**

Clients should be able to make common content edits without involving a designer.

**Examples**

* “Update the About page with new staff”

* “Fix the wording on the Invisalign page”

* “Change our phone number site-wide”

**Technical Direction**

* Headless CMS

* AI layer interprets natural language instructions

* Edits apply across the site in near real time

**Safeguards**

* Scoped editing permissions

* Optional preview before publish

* Versioning or rollback preferred

---

### **4.3 Token System (Content)**

Content should also be tokenized where possible:

* Practice name

* Address

* Phone

* Staff listings

* Reusable service descriptions

This allows:

* Global updates

* Reduced error risk

* Faster AI execution

---

### **4.4 Human Support Escalation**

**Requirements**

* Always-visible “Request Support” or “Open Ticket” option

* Users can submit:

  * Design requests

  * Complex edits

  * Clarification requests

**Goal**

AI reduces workload—but never blocks access to humans.

---

## **5\. Technical & Architectural Notes (Non-Prescriptive)**

The implementation is flexible, but the system should support:

* Headless CMS architecture

* Token-driven theming

* Real-time UI updates

* AI text interpretation layer

* Persisted configurations

* Scalable industry content templates

Specific tools (e.g., Webflow, custom frontend, CMS choice, AI provider) are intentionally left open for developer recommendation.

---

## **6\. Success Criteria**

A successful implementation allows:

* A healthcare practice to feel the site is “already theirs” before purchase

* Sales demos to modify looks live

* Clients to make routine updates without support tickets

* Patientli’s team to focus on higher-value design and strategy work

---

## **7\. Out of Scope (for Initial Build)**

* Advanced CRM features

* Marketing automation

* Analytics dashboards

* Multi-location management

* Custom component builders

These may be considered future phases.
